In the early 1920s chastushki were used by Young Communists in organized village gatherings as a form of anti-religious propaganda, subjecting the church and the rural clergy to ridicule using the traditional rural poetic form.Lynne Viola, Peasant Rebels Under Stalin: Collectivization and the Culture of Peasant Resistance. New York: Oxford University Press, 1996; pg. 50. Scholar Lynne Viola provides one such example of an anti-religious Soviet rhyme, rendered here in literal English translation: